post_text: East Boston Neighborhood Health Center is offering free COVID-19 testing in East Boston. See below for more information --
shared_text:
East Boston Neighborhood Health Center
September 1 at 6:25 PM ·

EBNHC is providing walk-thru COVID-19 testing at Central Square Park, 201 Border Street in East Boston from Tuesday, September 1 through Saturday, September 12. No appointment needed but registration required. Pre-register by calling 617-568-4500 for quicker testing. You do not need to have symptoms to get tested. Testing is free to the patient.

Tuesday, Thursday, and Friday: 2pm to 6:30pm
Wednesday: 9am to 2:30pm
Saturday: 10am to 2:30pm

Available via T bus routes 114, 116, 117, 120, and 121. Limited parking available.

We also provide testing at Orleans Street in East Boston. Details at ebnhc.org/covid19

post_text:
Meal Service Update:
Excel Academy will continue to provide free breakfast and lunch. Families can pick up multiple days’ worth of meals at Excel Academy Chelsea (180 2nd Street, Chelsea, MA 02150) and Excel Academy Charter High School (401 Bremen Street, East Boston, MA 02128). Meals are available from 10:00am – 12:00pm on Tuesdays and Thursdays. The last day of this meal service will be Thursday, September 10th. When school starts there will be a new schedule for meal pick up. More information coming soon.

Excel Academy continuará brindando desayuno y almuerzo gratis. Las familias ahora pueden recoger comidas de varios días en Excel Academy Chelsea (180 2nd Street, Chelsea, MA 02150) y Excel Academy Charter High School (401 Bremen Street, East Boston, MA 02128). Nuestro horario es martes y jueves de 10:00 a.m. a 12:00 p.m. El último día de este servicio de comidas será el jueves 10 de septiembre. Cuando comience la escuela, habrá un nuevo horario para recoger las comidas. Más información próximamente.

post_text:
The Five Stages of Grief is one of the foundational theories, but many thought something was missing and that the model didn't capture the true cycle of grief. So, two stages were added - shock & disbelief AND guilt. This article explains each stage & provides an outlet to seek support through online counseling for those interested: bit.ly/thrivetalkxlhs

Las cinco etapas del dolor son una de las teorías fundamentales, pero muchos pensaron que faltaba algo y que el modelo no capturó el verdadero ciclo del dolor. Entonces se agregaron dos etapas: conmoción e incredulidad Y culpa. Este artículo explica cada etapa y proporciona una salida para buscar apoyo a través de consejos en línea para aquellos interesados: bit.ly/thrivetalkxlhs

#griefisreal #survivinggrief #griefandloss #wavesofgrief #teengrief #excelacademycharterschool

post_text:
"Grief, I've learned, is really just love. It's all the love you want to give but cannot. All of that unspent love gathers up in the corner of your eyes, the lump in your throat, and in the hollow part of your chest. Grief is just love with no place to go."

"El dolor, he aprendido, es realmente solo amor. Es todo el amor que quieres dar pero no puedes. Todo ese amor no gastado se acumula en el rabillo de tus ojos, el nudo en tu garganta y en la parte hueca de tu pecho. La pena es solo amor sin un lugar a donde ir ". #excelacademyhomeschoolcharter

post_text: As a community, we are grieving. The uncertainty and loss that has accompanied the Covid-19 pandemic, the senseless loss of life due to police brutality, and, most recently, the tragic passing of one of our former students, has left many of us with heavy hearts. Grief is hard to define and hard to process. This article helps us get started with defining and understanding grief.

post_text:
We wanted to follow up our post last week featuring Bryan Stevenson, to provide more context around his Equal Justice Initiative (EJI). EJI is a human rights organization founded by Bryan Stevenson in Montgomery, Alabama. The EJI has been successful in their work with “eliminating excess and unfair sentencing, exonerating innocent death row prisoners, confronting abuse of the incarcerated and mentally ill and aiding children prosecuted as adults.” @eji_org.

The photo features a project taken on by the EJI staff to memorialize this history. The details include visiting hundreds of lynching sites, collecting soil, and erecting public markers, in an effort to reshape the cultural landscape with monuments and memorials that more truthfully and accurately reflect our history. More details on the EJI initiative can be found here: https://eji.org/bryan-stevenson/ Photo Credit Shyan Brown.

text:

post_text: This Friday at 11am on Bennington Street right in front of Excel Academy East Boston, we will be hosting – “Juneteenth”. A festival held on the nineteenth of June by African Americans, especially in the southern states, to commemorate emancipation from slavery. We will come together as a community to line the street and show our support. Bring your signs, wear your shirts and masks, or XL swag to represent and support The Black Lives Matters movement. Bring the children, your dogs, your significant others, bring your friends, neighbors, etc. There will be light refreshments and some other surprises! Also please note, social distancing measures will be taken. #excelacademycharterschool #quedarseencasayexcel #stayhomeandexcel

post_text: We would like all of our seniors to feel like they are seen and remembered since they won’t be able to see the people that they affected and cared for them. In pursuit of this goal, we are asking for members of the greater Excel community to Sponsor a Senior. Sponsoring a senior will mean providing a Love Lock or Luminary. More details can be found on our news & announcements page under “Support a 2020 Graduate” #quedarseencasayexcel #stayhomeandexcel

post_text:
We stand together.
We stand together against police brutality and racism.
We stand together as our students, families, and staff raise their voice against injustice of Black/African American people.
Permanecemos juntos en solidaridad.
Permanecemos unidos en contra la brutalidad policial y el racismo.
Permanecemos unidos con nuestros estudiantes, familias, y personal que están usando sus voces en contra de las injusticias hacia las vidas de personas Afrodecendientes. #blacklivesmatter

post_text:
Posted from @excel_be_well. Encouraging words.
Dearest family: take the time to process and hold yourself with the kindest and most loving embrace while you take a moment to recover between protesting/resisting/taking action. Journal. Sing. Speak. Sleep. Eat. Rest. Fuel and refuel that tank. Don’t allow yourself to get to empty. We need you. Be well, fam. 🔆 #StayHomeandExcel #QuedarseEnCasaYExcel #bewell #blacklivesmatter

post_text:
Students,

As we are all dealing with school closings and the delay of spring sports, the MCSAO is challenging your school community to stay active through the MCSAO Spring At Home Workout Challenge.

Each day, we will post a new video to our YouTube channel:
https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCQzozQ9v3F_pt-BL3q91UjQ

This will feature a variety of MCSAO AD’s, PE Teachers and Coaches. Schools will be competing with one another, so once you have completed the workout, you will to track it daily using the google form (https://forms.gle/V9s91PwRm3r5tk1N7), and the school with the most points (you get 1 point for completing each workout each day) will be crowned the winners.

Spread the word, and encourage your entire school community to get involved.

MCSAO

post_text:
This evening, we are hosting An Evening with Charlie Davies.

For those who do not know, Charlie Davies is a former US Men's National Team Soccer player who has played professional soccer in Sweden, France, Denmark and here in the Boston area for the New England Revolution. His story is inspirational, and he is coming to the High School this evening (June 17th) to meet our students and to tell his story.

The event starts at 5:00pm and costs $5, and you will get the chance to enter a raffle to win a signed US MNT jersey, and or a signed Chelsea FC/NE Revs flag.

This event is open to the entire Excel community.

post_text:
Boston Planning & Development Agency - puertas abiertas sobre el transporte en East Boston. Este evento es parte de la conversación general de cómo se ha de preservar, mejorar y crecer en East Boston. En esta reunión se solicitará la participación de la comunidad acerca de cómo viaja hoy y cómo podemos pensar en futuro. Independientemente de si viajas a pie, en bici, tomas el autobús o el tren, manejas o vas en auto
en East Boston, queremos escucharte. El equipo compartirá información sobre otros estudios de planificación ya completados o en proceso y lo que hemos oído en reuniones públcas anteriores.
Este evento es parte de la multitud de eventos públicos de PLAN: East Boston, una iniciativa de planeamiento a largo plazo, que cuando se complete, actualizará el Plan Maestro de East Boston y recomendará cambios en la zonificación de East Boston.
Dispondremos de aperitivos, materiales traducidos y servicios de interpretación.

East Boston High School Gymnasium
86 White St, East Boston, MA 02128
6:30 pm - 8:00 pm
12 de marzo de 2019

There will be a community workshop focusing on open space in East Boston. Open space includes parks, playgrounds, community gardens, beaches, boardwalks, marshes, and more. The workshop—part of a broader conversation on how to preserve, enhance, and grow East Boston—will solicit community feedback about what our open space needs are today and how open spaces should be used in the future.

For more details visit the NEWS section of our website

We are also grateful for our students, who not only contribute so much to our school community, but also our greater Boston and Chelsea communities.

A prime example of this is HS Senior Jade Darling, who has been a member of Excel’s soccer and basketball teams and is also a member of the Black Student Union and National Honor Society. Outside of Excel, Jade has been involved in the Big Sister Association of Greater Boston program and was recently celebrated at an event with Mayor Walsh.

You can learn more about Jade, her involvement with the Big Sister program and how she was able to meet with someone you might all recognize. https://youtu.be/YBT5sO2Pia4

post_text:
Check out our awesome students learning about the medical field this summer! Sade Olatunbosun and Kay Miranda attended the Northeastern University Pre-College Accelerate program in July learning about careers in medicine. Isabella Sampaio and 2 other students (Lyn Miranda and Aaliyah Delvalle Ortiz) attended Harvard University HMS MEDscience Program where they learned CPR and how to care for robotic patients. Ariana Martinez attended Brandeis Global Youth Summit, completing a team research project in addition to conducting lab work. Jovan Tormes Vaquerano and Ruben Martinez attended CURE at Dana Farber/Harvard Cancer Center engaging in sustained medical research on different cancer treatments.
#CAPSteam #CollegeAccessEXCELence #Excel4lifee

post_text: How are you spending your summer vacation? Rising senior, Karyn Padilla just completed a summer internship working at The Massachusetts State House. During her time, she was announced on the House floor, got to engage with other interns at the summer speaker series, and debated immigration reform while playing the role of US Senators in the Edward M Kennedy Institute's replica Senate Chamber and had the opportunity to hear from reporters on their experience of covering state government. To have your summer experience featured, send us a message.

post_text: Wolves Nation news update: History was made this past week, as all of our Spring sports teams were victorious! Congrats to our baseball team ⚾️ on their first win of the season, our softball team on hitting 5 home runs in one game to record their 4th W, our volleyball boys 🏐 earning their 3rd win of the season and both our boys and girls track teams on starting their season 2-0. Spring is here, and it’s time for Wolves Nation to ROAR!

Spring is here, and it’s time for Wolves Nation to ROAR!

post_text: As Black History month wraps up, Excel Academy welcomed Dr. Kellie Carter Jackson, who is a 19th century historian in the Department of Africana Studies at Wellesley College, to drop some knowledge on our student body! We also had our school band perform the legendary song Stand By Me by Ben E King, and heard an uplifting performance of the civil rights anthem "Lift Every Voice and Sing". #blackhistory #knowledgeispower
